baseline.response:
Set the optional field explicitly to `null`; do not omit it or pass `undefined`. In Jazz update patches, omitted/`undefined` properties mean "leave current value alone", while `null` is the persisted clear value for a nullable optional ref/value.

```ts
await project.update({
  projectId: null,
});
```

Make sure the schema permits this, e.g. `projectId: z.string().nullable().optional()` or the Jazz schema equivalent for an optional nullable ref.

Use accessors/functions for query inputs so the query can re-run when those inputs change.

Svelte:
```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  let projectId = $state<string | undefined>();
  const tasks = createQuery(() => ({
    table: "tasks",
    where: { projectId },
  }));
</script>
```

Solid:
```ts
const [projectId, setProjectId] = createSignal<string | undefined>();

const tasks = createQuery(() => ({
  table: "tasks",
  where: { projectId: projectId() },
}));
```

The key shape is `createQuery(() => queryArgs)`, with every reactive input read inside the function.

Write the test around sets/maps keyed by stable row IDs, not array order.

```ts
const alice = await createTestClient("alice");
const bob = await createTestClient("bob");

const ids = await Promise.all([
  alice.db.tasks.create({ title: "a" }),
  alice.db.tasks.create({ title: "b" }),
  bob.db.tasks.create({ title: "c" }),
]);

await waitForSync([alice, bob]);

const aliceRows = await alice.db.tasks.query({}).all();
const bobRows = await bob.db.tasks.query({}).all();

expect(new Set(aliceRows.map((r) => r.id))).toEqual(new Set(ids));
expect(new Set(bobRows.map((r) => r.id))).toEqual(new Set(ids));
expect(Object.fromEntries(aliceRows.map((r) => [r.id, r.title]))).toEqual(
  Object.fromEntries(bobRows.map((r) => [r.id, r.title])),
);
```

Only sort by an explicit application field if order is part of the behavior under test.

Create Alice and Bob clients, have Alice create a row whose policy only grants Alice, then assert Bob cannot observe or mutate it through public APIs.

```ts
const alice = await signInTestUser("alice");
const bob = await signInTestUser("bob");

const row = await alice.db.privateNotes.create({ body: "secret", ownerId: alice.user.id });
await waitForSync(alice);

await expect(bob.db.privateNotes.get(row.id)).resolves.toBeNull();
await expect(
  bob.db.privateNotes.update(row.id, { body: "stolen" }),
).rejects.toMatchObject({ code: "permission_denied" });

await expect(alice.db.privateNotes.get(row.id)).resolves.toMatchObject({ body: "secret" });
```

Cover both negative read and negative write; then verify Alice's row was not changed.

After writing the file metadata and chunks, wait for edge/server durability before reporting upload success.

```ts
const file = await jazz.files.createFromBlob(blob, { name: blob.name, type: blob.type });
await upload.update({ fileId: file.id, status: "uploaded" });
await file.waitForSync?.();
await upload.waitForSync?.();
```

On download, check whether all required chunks are present locally. If not, render a loading/retry state and request/sync the missing chunks before creating the Blob/object URL. Do not treat partial local chunk availability as a valid completed download.

Use two clients connected to the same test sync server, pause/disconnect propagation, make both clients observe the same base version, then write conflicting updates before reconnecting.

```ts
const a = await createTestClient("alice");
const b = await createTestClient("bob");
const row = await a.db.items.create({ count: 0, title: "base" });
await waitForVisible(b, row.id);

await a.network.pause();
await b.network.pause();

await Promise.all([
  a.db.items.update(row.id, { title: "from-a" }),
  b.db.items.update(row.id, { title: "from-b" }),
]);

await Promise.all([a.network.resume(), b.network.resume()]);
await waitForSync([a, b]);

expect(await a.db.items.get(row.id)).toEqual(await b.db.items.get(row.id));
```

The critical part is the paused propagation window; otherwise the second writer may simply build on the first instead of creating a genuine concurrent frontier.

Use a development build with the Jazz native runtime; Expo Go is not sufficient. Install the React Native Jazz packages, add the Jazz config/plugin to Metro/Expo as required by the package, run codegen if your schema requires it, and wrap the app in the React Native Jazz provider.

Typical shape:
```tsx
import { JazzProvider } from "jazz-tools/react-native";

export default function App() {
  return (
    <JazzProvider sync={{ peer: process.env.EXPO_PUBLIC_JAZZ_SYNC_URL }}>
      <RootNavigator />
    </JazzProvider>
  );
}
```

Then rebuild the native app with `expo prebuild`/development build tooling so native storage and runtime modules are actually present.

Keep Jazz rows at the infrastructure boundary and expose typed domain structs/services above them. Use `QueryBuilder`/table APIs to fetch raw Jazz values, decode them into Rust types with explicit validation, and centralize writes in repository methods.

Shape:
```rust
struct Project { id: RowId, name: String }

impl ProjectRepo {
    async fn get(&self, id: RowId) -> Result<Option<Project>> {
        let row = self.ctx.table("projects").get(id).await?;
        row.map(decode_project).transpose()
    }

    async fn rename(&self, id: RowId, name: String) -> Result<()> {
        self.ctx.table("projects").update(id, value!({ "name": name })).await
    }
}
```

This keeps schema/value decoding errors localized and prevents arbitrary application code from depending on untyped row maps.

Verify the caller's auth token at the service boundary, create a session/request-scoped Jazz context for that caller, perform the update through that context, then wait until the backend/server can observe the result before responding.

Endpoint shape:
```rust
async fn update_project(State(app): State<App>, claims: Claims, Json(input): Json<Input>) -> Result<Json<Project>> {
    let ctx = app.jazz.for_authenticated_user(claims.subject).await?;
    ctx.table("projects").update(input.id, value!({ "name": input.name })).await?;
    ctx.wait_for_durable().await?;

    let visible = app.backend_ctx.table("projects").get(input.id).await?;
    Ok(Json(decode_project(visible)?))
}
```

The important pieces are caller-scoped permission evaluation, write attribution to the caller, and an explicit durability/visibility wait before returning a server-visible result.

loaded.response:
Create one server-only `JazzContext` at process/app startup and reuse it across requests. In Node.js, install `jazz-napi` as a direct dependency and use a persistent driver for durable local state:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});

process.once("SIGTERM", async () => {
  await jazz.shutdown();
});
```

Key constraints: do not create a context per request; give persistent backends a stable `dataPath`; only use `{ type: "memory" }` when connected to an upstream durable `serverUrl`; keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only and out of public-prefixed env vars; use `backendSecret` for server-connected backend/request-scoped authority; wait for the required durability tier before returning success from endpoints that promise persisted or globally visible writes; call `shutdown()` when the process owner exits.

Use `null`, not `undefined`, when clearing an optional Jazz column. In an update payload, `undefined` means “leave this field unchanged.”

```ts
await db.update(app.todos, todoId, {
  projectId: null,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Omit `.wait(...)` if the UI only needs the optimistic local update.

When query inputs are reactive, pass an accessor/function so the binding rebuilds the query as inputs change.

Svelte:
```ts
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
);
```

Solid:
```ts
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
}));
```

Passing an already-built query captures the current input value instead of tracking later changes.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two independent optimistic UI writes that should appear together after the callback commits, then settle as one direct batch.

```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Use `db.transaction(...)` when the writes must remain staged until authority accepts them and then become globally visible together.

```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Build a small typed layer at the Rust row boundary instead of pretending Jazz queries are generated or compile-time typed. Define each query projection once with `QueryBuilder`, keep its selected column order next to a fallible decoder, and decode `Vec<(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)>` into strict app structs.

Use `SchemaBuilder`/`TableSchema::builder` for schema construction and `row_input!` for writes. For reads, reject wrong projection lengths, unexpected `Value` variants, and `Value::Null` except where the schema is nullable. For writes, expose typed functions that accept domain structs or command types, convert them to `row_input!`/`Value`, call `insert` or `update`, and return the `BatchId` so the caller can await the required durability tier.

Pattern:
```rust
struct TodoRow { id: ObjectId, title: String, done: bool }

fn todo_query() -> QueryBuilder {
    QueryBuilder::new("todos").select(["title", "done"])
}

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    match values {
        [Value::Text(title), Value::Boolean(done)] => Ok(TodoRow {
            id,
            title: title.clone(),
            done: *done,
        }),
        _ => Err(AppError::SchemaDecode("todos projection mismatch")),
    }
}
```

Centralize this per table/use case so handlers never decode positional values ad hoc.

Use a real local sync topology, but make the assertion independent of query order. Create two memory clients against `startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true })`, write the rows with Alice, await edge durability, then poll Bob until he observes the same set sorted by a stable key.

```ts
it("syncs several rows regardless of delivery order", async () => {
  const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  const clients: Db[] = [];

  try {
    const alice = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
    const bob = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
    clients.push(alice, bob);

    await Promise.all([
      alice.insert(app.todos, { key: "a", title: "Alpha" }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.todos, { key: "b", title: "Beta" }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.todos, { key: "c", title: "Gamma" }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
    ]);

    await vi.waitFor(async () => {
      const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
      const observed = rows
        .map((row) => ({ key: row.key, title: row.title }))
        .sort((left, right) => left.key.localeCompare(right.key));

      expect(observed).toEqual([
        { key: "a", title: "Alpha" },
        { key: "b", title: "Beta" },
        { key: "c", title: "Gamma" },
      ]);
    });
  } finally {
    await Promise.all(clients.map((client) => client.shutdown()));
    await server.stop();
  }
});
```

If the app schema supports explicit ordering, use that in the query. Otherwise normalize by a stable field as shown; do not assert raw array order.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` for a narrow row-policy test. Assert Bob cannot see Alice's row, and independently assert Bob cannot mutate it. Denied reads should resolve to an empty result, while denied writes should reject through `expectDenied`.

```ts
import { createPolicyTestApp, type PolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import permissions from "../permissions";
import { app } from "../schema";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

it("denies Bob read and write access to Alice's row", async () => {
  const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
  const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

  const todo = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Alice private todo", done: false }).value;

  await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: todo.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);

  bob.expectDenied((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Bob should not edit this" }),
  );

  alice.expectAllowed((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Alice can still edit this" }),
  );
});
```

Add separate denied `delete` or `insert` assertions only if the policy grants those operations independently; read and update should not be treated as covering every operation.
